      "if it exists, and the Lean statement is to prove `sorry ↔ ...`, which is literally proving that `∃ A, ...` is true or false depending on what is replaced in `sorry`. \n\nAlternatively, the problem is constructed in such a way that perhaps the answer is unknown (as per Erdős), and the Lean formalization is asking to prove that the right side is true if and only if the `sorry` is true. \n\nBut perhaps we can give an `A` for which this works. \n\nLet me try to take `A = ∅`. Then:\n\n1. The condition becomes `∃ᶠ n in atTop, true`, because for `A = ∅`, there are no `a ∈ A`, so the `∀ a ∈ A` statement is automatically true. \n   - So this condition is satisfied (since it's true for all `n`, and thus for infinitely many `n`).\n2. The density condition is `liminf (0 / π(n)) = 0 > 0`, which is false. \n\nHmm, not good. \n\nAlternatively, take `A = ℕ_{>0} = {1, 2, ...}`:\n1. The condition is `∀ a ∈ ℕ_{>0}, 0 < a < n → (n - a) prime`.\n   - But for any `n`, we can take `a = 1`, and then `n - 1` is not always prime. For example, take `n = 4`, `n - 1 = 3` (prime), but `a = 2`, `n - 2 = 2` (prime). But `a = 3`, `n - 3 = 1`, not prime. \n   - So it doesn't work for infinitely many `n`.\n\nBut we need a set where there are infinitely many `n` such that for all `a ∈ A`, if `0 < a < n` then `n - a` is prime. \n\nConsider `A = {1}`:\n1. We need that for infinitely many `n`, if `0 < 1 < n` (i.e., `n ≥ 3`), then `n - 1` is prime. \n   - The condition becomes: there are infinitely many primes `p`, because we can take `n = p + 1`, then `n - 1 = p` is prime. \n   - Indeed, `A = {1}` works because we can take `n = p + 1` for any prime `p`, so `n - 1 = p` is prime. There are infinitely many such `n`, so the first condition is satisfied.\n2. The density condition is `liminf ( |{1} ∩ {1, ..., n}| / π(n) ) = liminf (1 / π(n)) = 0`. \n   - So `0 > 0` is false. \n\nThus, `A = {1}` satisfies the first condition but not the second.\n\nLet's try another approach: take `A` to be the set of perfect squares `A = {1, 4, 9, 16, ...}`:\n1. The first condition: for infinitely many `n`, for all perfect squares `a ∈ A`, `0 < a < n → n - a` prime. \n   - This seems hard to satisfy for any `n`, because `a = 1` would require `n - 1` prime, and `a = 4` would require `n - 4` prime, etc. \n\nBut perhaps take `A` to be very sparse. The only way this would work is if we can choose `A` such that there are infinitely many `n` with `n - a` prime for each `a ∈ A`. \n\nHmm. \n\nAnother thought: perhaps take `A = {2}`. Then we need for infinitely many `n`, when `0 < 2 < n`, we have `n - 2` prime. This would mean that there are infinitely many `n` such that `n - 2` is prime. Take `n = p + 2`, for `p` prime. As primes are infinite, there are infinitely many such `n`. So condition (1) is satisfied. \n\nDensity condition:\n`liminf (|{2} ∩ {1, ..., n}| / π(n)) = liminf (if 2 ≤ n then 1 else 0) / π(n)`. \n\nAs `n → ∞`, `π(n) → ∞`, and `(if 2 ≤ n then 1 else 0) ≤ 1`, so the ratio tends to 0. Thus, the liminf is 0. The condition `0 > 0` is false. Not good. \n\nNext, try `A = {1, 2}`. The first condition requires that for infinitely many `n`, for all `a ∈ {1, 2}` with `0 < a < n`, `n - a` is prime. \n\nThis means:\nFor all `n`, if `n ≥ 3`, we need `n - 1` and `n - 2` to be prime. \n\nAre there infinitely many `n` such that both `n - 1` and `n - 2` are prime? \n\nAn example is `n = 6`: `n - 1 = 5`, `n - 2 = 4`, no. \n\n`n = 4`: `n - 1 = 3`, `n - 2 = 2`, yes. \n\n`n = 8`: `n - 1 = 7`, `n - 2 = 6`, no. \n\n`n = 5`: `n - 1 = 4`, `n - 2 = 3`, no. \n\n`n = 12`: `n - 1 = 11`, `n - 2 = 10`, no. \n\n`n = 6` doesn't work. \n\nHowever, if we take `n = 5 + 2 = 7`: `n - 1 = 6`, no. \n\nThis seems hard. \n\nAlternatively, try `A = {3}`:\n1. For `n = p + 3`, we have `n - 3 = p`, so `n - 3` prime. \n   - The condition becomes: if `3 < n`, then `n - 3` is prime, i.e., `n = p + 3` for some prime `p`. \n   - Since there are infinitely many primes `p`, we can take `n = p + 3`, so there are infinitely man